xwayland: fix NULL-pointer dereference / SIGSEGV when libxcvt_gen_mode_info() fails (ms178-2)

Root cause of the deterministic Xwayland crash seen in the journal:

    (EE)  3: /usr/bin/Xwayland (xwayland_modeinfo_from_cvt)
    (EE)  7: /usr/lib/libffi.so.8 (ffi_call+0x166)
    (EE)  8: /usr/lib/libwayland-client.so.0 (wl_display_dispatch...)
    (EE) Segmentation fault at address 0x10
    (EE) Caught signal 11 (Segmentation fault). Server aborting

The symbolicated, GCC-built backtrace shows the faulting instruction is
`mov 0x10(%rax),%rdx` in xwayland_modeinfo_from_cvt(): %rax is the return value
of libxcvt_gen_mode_info(), and offset 0x10 is the `dot_clock` member of
`struct libxcvt_mode_info`. The fault address 0x10 therefore proves
libxcvt_gen_mode_info() returned NULL and Xwayland dereferenced it unchecked
(hw/xwayland/xwayland-cvt.c). This is NOT a toolchain miscompile of
libffi/libwayland (those merely marshal the Wayland output/mode event that
drives the code path); it is a missing NULL check in Xwayland's own source.

libffi/libwayland appear in the backtrace only because the mode is created in
response to a Wayland output "mode" event, dispatched through libffi's ffi_call.

Fix: make xwayland_modeinfo_from_cvt() return Bool and propagate failure out of
xwayland_cvt() as a NULL RRModePtr. Every existing caller of xwayland_cvt()
(output_get_rr_modes(), xwl_output_get_xrandr_modes()) already checks for a NULL
return and handles it correctly (skip the fake mode, or FatalError on genuine
OOM for the primary mode), so no caller changes are required.

Signed-off-by: ms178
--- a/hw/xwayland/xwayland-cvt.c
+++ b/hw/xwayland/xwayland-cvt.c
@@ -29,7 +29,7 @@
 
 #include "xwayland-cvt.h"
 
-static void
+static Bool
 xwayland_modeinfo_from_cvt(xRRModeInfo *modeinfo,
                            int hdisplay, int vdisplay, float vrefresh,
                            Bool reduced, Bool interlaced)
@@ -39,6 +39,15 @@
     libxcvt_mode_info =
         libxcvt_gen_mode_info(hdisplay, vdisplay, vrefresh, reduced, interlaced);
 
+    /* libxcvt_gen_mode_info() can return NULL (e.g. allocation failure). The
+     * result was previously dereferenced unconditionally, causing a NULL
+     * dereference at offset 0x10 (->dot_clock) — a hard SIGSEGV that aborts the
+     * whole Xwayland server. This is reached from a Wayland output/mode event
+     * via wl_display_dispatch, so a transient failure would kill the session.
+     * Fail gracefully instead and let the caller decide what to do. */
+    if (!libxcvt_mode_info)
+        return FALSE;
+
     modeinfo->width      = libxcvt_mode_info->hdisplay;
     modeinfo->height     = libxcvt_mode_info->vdisplay;
     modeinfo->dotClock   = libxcvt_mode_info->dot_clock * 1000.0;
@@ -51,6 +60,8 @@
     modeinfo->modeFlags  = libxcvt_mode_info->mode_flags;
 
     free(libxcvt_mode_info);
+
+    return TRUE;
 }
 
 RRModePtr
@@ -60,8 +71,10 @@
     char name[128];
     xRRModeInfo modeinfo = { 0, };
 
-    xwayland_modeinfo_from_cvt(&modeinfo,
-                               hdisplay, vdisplay, vrefresh, reduced, interlaced);
+    if (!xwayland_modeinfo_from_cvt(&modeinfo,
+                                    hdisplay, vdisplay, vrefresh,
+                                    reduced, interlaced))
+        return NULL;
 
     /* Horizontal granularity in libxcvt is 8, so if our horizontal size is not
      * divisible by 8, libxcvt will round it up, and we will advertise a wrong
